review_blob:
Im rating this as if it were a beer (even though its not). For this not-beer, the aroma is super sweet, and the flavors even more so. In fact, its so sweet that it really should only be poured over ice cream.

This is not beer. Let me repeat: THIS IS NOT BEER! If this were a root beer rating website, this drink would have gotten higher marks. But this is a beer rating website so it gets my lowest rating ever.
beer_name: Small Town Not Your Fathers Root Beer (5.9%)

review_blob: Yellowish orange. Thick, frothy head. Bready malts, lemony aromas, some tangy citrus akin to grapefruit or tangerine. A really nice, really drinkable IPA.
Pours a cloudy lemony yellow. Two inch head. Honey lemongrass, wheat on the nose. Heavy carbonation. Funky earthy flavors, very herbal. A very drinkable summer ale.
Pours clear golden yellow. Thick, frothy head. Big lemon flavors. Overpowers everything else. Not that great.

Pours an opaque, unfiltered amber, pretty frothy head, lots of lacing. Oak, vanilla, caramel on the nose. Creamy mouthfeel. Hoppy bitterness offset by sweetness from vanilla, caramel, toffee notes. Bitter at the front; sweet and smooth at the back. A really enjoyable IPA. A solid, drinkable beer.

Pours a hazy golden copper, little head and lacing. Roasted malts, caramel on the nose. Creamy mouth fell, plenty of floral, bread, resin notes. Toffee, straw, caramel. An amazing extra pale ale. Delicious!
beer_name: Odell St. Lupulin Extra Pale Ale

review_blob: Somewhat disappointed. Bottle was over-carbonated so upon opening, the beer spilled out onto the counter. I was only able to save about half of it. That being said, the beer pours a cloud dull gold, no head or lacing. Tangy, citrus aromas. Somewhat bubbly mouthfeel, big sour notes. Hints of grapefruit, tart lemon, wheat. Lots of yeast and brett all around. This is a nice, funky beer, but it wasnt carbonated properly, which is disappointing.
Pours a cloudy golden yellow, super frothy (too frothy even due to slight over-carbonation). Brett, citrus aromas. Slightly crisp, very sour, pretty sweet citrus notes. Overall, pretty nice sour ale.

Wow. This one?s a shocker. Pours a dark reddish brown, frothy head, decent lacing. Sour, tangy aromas, hints of molasses and dark fruit. Heavily carbonated, medium bodied. Not as sour as I expected, mostly offset by the roasted malts and hints of brown sugar. This is one surprising, interesting beer. Im a fan.
beer_name: Jester King Commercial Suicide Oaked Farmhouse Mild (Batch 6+)

review_blob: Pours a clear gold. Thick head, lemony aromas. Grapefruit, lemon flavors, hints of hops. Nice ale.
Pours a golden lemony yellow. Citrus aromas: lemon, tangerine, hibiscus. Very sweet, slightly oily. Sweet Belgian yeast, lemon, honey, candied sugar. A nice trippel.

Pours a dark, reddish brown. Roasted malts, brown sugar on the nose. Start off with a bitter, hoppy flavor, then ends on notes of toffee, caramel, and brown sugar. Medium bodied, somewhat oily mouthfeel. An interesting take on the traditional style.

Pours a reddish orange, with half-inch head (pretty thick for a gose) and no lacing. Tart berries on the nose. Very crisp, tangy citrus with a very subtle saltiness (not as noticeable as it could have been). This is not as traditional as Westbrooks Gose, more akin to Sixpoints Jammer. Still very good, though. A nice one for a hot summer day.
Pours a yellowish orange. Some head and lacing. Aromas are hardly discernible. Thick mouthfeel, super bitter on the tip of the tongue. Resin, pine, grapefruit. Not bad, not great.

Solid IPA. Pours a coppery orange, hardly any head, bit of lacing. Very subtle malty aromas. Malty, nice grapefruit and other citrus flavors, not as bitter as I would have expected (you might call it halfway between pale ale and IPA, with tons of flavor). Crisp, slightly oily, very refreshing. This is the kind of beer that I could drink all day long.
Pours an opaque brown, thick head. Some caramel and brown sugar on the nose. Very malty, almost too much, overpowers the hoppy bitterness. This is a heavy beer, not my favorite but a solid ale.

Pours a cloudy, light yellow, no head or lacing. Subtle salty, citrus aromas. Less salt on the tongue than is typical of the style (akin to Sixpoint?s Jammer). Tart lemon, tangy grapefruit, ever so slightly hint of salt. Not what I expected but good nonetheless.

Pours a cloudy dark orange. Big aromas: lemon, pine, grapefruit, candied sugar. Big hoppy flavors, bready malts, lots of citrus. Very much in the West coast style in term of bitterness. Odd sweet aftertaste. Not my favorite IPA, but its still good.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Pours a hazy orange, decent head and lacing. Tangy, almost sour, citrus aromas. The tang of the grapefruit and the hoppy bitterness compete for attention as you drink. Citrus and hops dont complement each other. I think they should have aimed for a sour ale instead, which might have made this beer more interesting and drinkable.
Pours a cloudy gold. Huge frothy head, two inches or so. Belgian yeast, lemon, some sugar. A hoppy Belgian ale, slightly confusing in that respect but a very drinkable beer.
Pours a cloudy amber, decent lacing. Bready, malty aromas. Very sweet, too much so, lots of caramel. Not the greatest.
Pours a grapefruit orange, no head and lacing. Funky, flowery aromas. Tart, salty, tangy citrus. A pleasant surprise. Very drinkable.
Pours a dull gold, not much head or lacing. Lemon, honey, pine aromas. Hoppy with some bitter aftertaste but some sweet taste as well (caramel, honey, citrus). Very drinkable beer.
Thick, frothy head. Amber hues. Hoppy, resin aromas. Oily mouthfeel. Bready malts, bitterness complimented by some lemon and caramel flavors. Nice IPA (almost a DIPA).
beer_name: Oskar Blues Deviant Dales India Pale Ale

review_blob: 12 oz. bottle. Pours a dark brown with reddish hues. Medium head, not much lacing. Oily mouthfeel, seems to coat the tongue. Roasted malts and candied sugar on the nose. Bready, malty with characteristic Belgian yeast. Sweet dark fruit on the tongue, hints of oaky vanilla and raisins toward the end. A very satisfying Belgian ale from a great brewery.
Pours a cloudy orangish yellow, huge frothy head and lacing. Pine, grapefruit, lemon on the nose. Citrus throughout, followed by a hefty helping of hops. Nicely balanced.
Pours a tangerine yellow, slight head. Citrus aromas. Grapefruit and other tangy citrus. Hoppy bitterness perfectly balanced with floral aromas and citrus flavors. A beautiful IPA!

Pours an amber with half-inch head, decent lacing. Sweet malts, caramel, some brown sugar. Slightly creamy mouthfeel. Malty with motes of honey, followed by bitterness at the back of the tongue. A very drinkable offering from Yards.
Pours a dark reddish copper, frothy off-white head, decent lacing. Hoppy citrus aromas. Oily mouthfeel. Pine, resin, butterscotch, caramel. Nice IPA.

Pours a amber, orangish in certain light. Frothy off-white head, nice lacing. Hops, brown sugar, caramel on the nose. Creamy, slightly oily mouthfeel. Butterscotch, toffee, caramel, resin. This is a great triple IPA. Hoppy bitterness and malty sweetness complement each other.

16 oz. can from Carton. Pours a slightly hazy light yellow. No head or lacing. An tangy aroma, somewhat pungent (but not in a bad way). Acerbic, citrus flavors, fairly crisp mouthfeel despite the sour notes. All in all, this is an excellent summer sour.
Pours a dark copper, decent head. Rich bourbon aromas. Creamy, oily mouthfeel. Some sweetness on the tongue from the malts, followed by a bitter hoppy aftertaste. Very boozy. Nice IIPA.
Pours a cranberry red, some head and lacing. Richer aromas than the blackboard. Very tart, raspberry. Tad bit oily mouthfeel. Easy drinking...

Pours a dark raspberry red (beautiful!). Very little head. Plum, berries on the nose. Yeasty, tart citrus flavors. Crisp, clean mouthfeel. Super smooth. I could drink this all day long on a hot summer weekend.

Pours a dark brown, nearly black. Very little head, no lacing to speak of. Aromas of roasted coffee beans, malt, toffee. Slightly creamy mouthfeel. Coffee beans, vanilla, hints of oak, some spices. Medium carbonation. Lingering aftertaste, roasted beans and malt.
beer_name: Flying Dog Brewhouse Rarities: Earl Grey Black Wheat

review_blob: Pours a cloudy orange, decent lacing. Bready, citrus aromas. Crisp, bitter at the back of the tongue. Grapefruit, straw, hint of lemon. A very drinkable IPA.

beer_brewer_name: St. John Brewers - The Tap Room
review_blob: Pours a clear orange, little to no head or lacing. Hefty mango and pineapple aromas. Somewhat oily mouthfeel. Dull fruity flavors, bland aftertaste. Not very appealing.
beer_name: St. John Brewers Virgin Islands Tropical Mango Pale Ale

review_blob: Pours an orangish amber with decent head and lacing. Malty, pine aromas. Bready, creamy, malt forward.
beer_name: Great Lakes Rye of the Tiger

review_blob: 12 oz. bottle. Pours a clear bronzish yellow. Hardly any head, no lacing. Crisp mouthfeel. Tart berries on the nose. Tartness on the tip of the tongue, followed by salty, sour aftertaste. Nice example of the style.
beer_name: Anderson Valley Highway 128 The Kimmie, The Yink, and the Holy Gose

review_blob: Pours a cloudy orange with half inch head. Oily mouthfeel. Resin, lemon on the nose. Hoppy bitterness. Overall, quite nice.

Pours a reddish amber with thick, frothy off-white head. Strong malt and caramel on the nose. The flavors come out immediately: huge malty sweetness on the tongue followed by hoppy bitterness. Big bodied ale, somewhat creamy mouthfeel. This thing is a whopper. Delicious.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: Pours a dark amber, thick frothy head. Oak, vanilla, caramel on the nose. Sweet, caramel malts, surprisingly lacking in bitterness for an IPA. Very drinkable though.
Pours a cloudy gold. Thin head, nice lacing. Floral aromas, honeysuckle. Herbal, earthy flavors. Nice summer ale.
Pours a dull gold, thick head, huge lacing. Oaky, smokey, citrus flavors. Semi-crisp mouthfeel. An odd but delightful ale.
beer_name: Against the Grain / Carton S.S. Kentucky

review_blob: Pours a golden amber. Creamy mouthfeel. Coffee beans, vanilla, peppermint. This isnt a bad beer, but its nowhere near as wonderful as Regular Coffee.
beer_name: Carton Irish Coffee Imperial Cream Ale

review_blob: Pours a clear off yellow, not much head. Acidic, bitter citrus on the nose. Bitter on the tongue, slightly sweet at the end. Nice sour ale.
Light coppery yellow. Subtle citrus aromas. Crisp, bitter flavors. Lemon zest, orange, grapefruit. Nice summer IPA.
beer_name: Boulevard Tasting Room Series Mid-Coast IPA

review_blob: Pours a dark, dark brown (almost black). No head or lacing. Strong bourbon and oak on the nose. Creamy mouthfeel, heavy bourbon notes throughout. Coffee notes are surprisingly mellow, compared to the original Kaldi. A nice barrel aged ale.
beer_name: Quest Kaldi Coffee Stout - Bourbon Barrel

review_blob: Pours a cloudy gold, substantial lacing. Robust aromas of peppers and veggies. Spices at the back of the tongue, an odd earthy mouthfeel. A wacky ale; not my favorite.

Pours a clear coppery yellow, heavy lacing. Pine and citrus aromas. Heavy dose of hoppy bitterness all the way through; some resin and pine, hints of lemon and grapefruit. Sure to please hopheads in the Greenville area.
